Nephrology is a branch of internal medicine dealing with the study of the function and diseases of the kidney. Nephrology concerns the diagnosis and treatment of kidney diseases, including electrolyte disturbances and hypertension, and the care of those requiring renal replacement therapy.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The purpose of the course is to provide basic competency in the field of nephrology. Requirements for students are the following: to study of the function and diseases of the kidney, to obtain  principles of diagnostics and treatment of kidney diseases, including electrolyte disturbances and hypertension, and the care of those requiring renal replacement therapy.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completion of the course the students will be able to: 1)	describe epidemiology, aetiology, pathogenesis, clinical symptoms of kidney diseases; 2)	demonstrate practical skills in acquiring a complete history and physical examination of patients with kidney diseases; 3)	use for differential diagnosis laboratory and radiology techniques as well as to interpretate the data; 4)	describe management of patients with different clinical syndromes: proteinuria, hematuria, nephritic syndrome, nephrotic syndrome, rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis, acute kidney injury and chronic renal failure; 5)	estimate renal function and  to manage patient in different stage of chronic kidney disease; 6)	do treatment decisions for chronic kidney disease patients and to send patients in time to nephrologists for the start of renal replacement therapy; 7)	know acute kidney injury signs and symptoms as well as treatment principles including necessity of renal replacement therapy.
